> Legend has it that in the late nineteenth century, the governor of Sichuan province, Ding Baozhen, was missing quite a few of his teeth. One day he ducked out of his palace to eat in a local restaurant, where the chef served him a dish of beautifully chopped up, quickly stir-fried ingredients. The governor was so impressed with the dish (not least because it was easy for him to eat), that he hired the chef full time and christened the recipe with his official name, Kung Bao. Though some people doubt the story, we're convinced it's the tooth.
> Sorry, we couldn't resist that one!

Boil a large #pot of water for your rice.

Thoroughly rinse your @Brown Basmati Rice{1} under cold water for about a minute. Add
the rice to the boiling water with @salt{1/4%tsp} and cook for around
~{20-25%minutes} until soft. Tip: Once cooked, drain the rice, put back in the
pot (off the heat) and cover with a clean #tea towel for ~{5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, finely chop the @Garlic Clove{2}(finely chopped) and @Red Chilli{1/2}(finely chopped). Peel
the @Ginger{1/2}(peeled and finely chopped) with the edge of a #spoon and finely
chop. Finely slice the @Spring Onion{3}(finely sliced, including the green part)
and chop the @Chestnut Mushrooms{1}(chopped in half or into large chunks). Separate
the @Broccoli{1/2}(separated into florets, cut in half) florets from the stalk and
cut them in half. Boil another #pot of water for the broccoli. Cook the broccoli
for about ~{3%minutes}, then drain.

== Kung Bao ==

To make the kung bao, whisk together the @Soy Sauce{3}, @Rice Vinegar{2} and
@?sugar{2%tsp} in a #small bowl.

Heat a #wok or large #frying pan{} over high heat and add @olive oil{1%tbsp}.
When hot, add the broccoli and cook for ~{1-2%minutes}. Add the mushrooms and
cook for a further ~{1-2%minutes} without moving the pan. Tip: If you stir the
mushrooms too often they won't get nice and brown!

Add the garlic, chilli (as much as you dare!), ginger, and three quarters of the
spring onion to the pan (reserving some of the green bits) and cook for
~{2%minutes}. Add the kung bao mix and cook for a further ~{1%minute}, then
remove the pan from the heat and stir in the @Cashew Nuts{2}.

Serve the rice into bowls, top with the kung bao and the remaining spring onion.
Tuck in!